  <section class="hero">
    <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
    <h1>What this is</h1>
    <p class="thesis">The Mexico Brief is a site about Mexico. Mostly the economy, politics, and the relationship with the US.</p>
    <p>I pull data from Banxico, INEGI, Hacienda, and other original sources and put it in one place, with the news that helps explain it. Everything is labeled with its source and date, and when something is my own opinion, I flag it. On top stories, the BE button has the background behind the headline.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>Why I made it</h2>
    <p>My name is <b>Alan Lacroix</b>. I was born in Mexico City and moved to Miami when I was young. I am building a business in Mexico now and visit often, and while doing so I realized I had lost touch with the social, but especially the political and economic, reality of the country. Peso at 17.5, good or bad? Minimum wage tripled in three years, why? Supermajority? How much of our economy goes to the US? I wanted to understand my country, rooted in facts, and come to my own conclusions.</p>
    <p>The numbers were all over the place and the news was sensationalist, so I built The Mexico Brief for myself, to pull from as many first-party data sources as possible and centralize them in one place. I found it extremely useful, started sharing it with family and friends, and they did as well. So I am opening it up.</p>
    <p>I view the country, admittedly, through a US lens. I am particularly interested in Mexico's political stability, economic growth, the relationship with the US (the trade agreement most recently), and how Mexico is taking advantage of AI, plus its position in the region in tech, private equity, and entrepreneurship.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
